1 📊 Overview.

This report identifies and analyzes outliers in the dataset using the IQR method, focusing on Income and Age variables.

2 📥 Load the Necessary Libraries

5 Calculating IQR values for Income and Age.

For Income:

# Calculate quartiles and IQR for income
income_q1 <- quantile(data$Income, 0.25)
income_q3 <- quantile(data$Income, 0.75)
income_iqr <- IQR(data$Income)

# Calculate boumds for Outliers
income_lower_bound <- income_q1 - 1.5 * income_iqr
income_upper_bound <- income_q3 - 1.5 * income_iqr

cat("Income IQR Analysis:\n")
## Income IQR Analysis:
cat("Q1:", income_q1, "\n")
## Q1: 41704.5
cat("Q3:", income_q3, "\n")
## Q3: 58151
cat("IQR:", income_iqr, "\n")
## IQR: 16446.5
cat("Lower Bound:", income_lower_bound, "\n")
## Lower Bound: 17034.75
cat("Upper Bound:", income_upper_bound, "\n")
## Upper Bound: 33481.25

For Age:

# Calculate quartiles and IQR for Age
age_q1 <- quantile(data$Age, 0.25)

age_iqr <- IQR(data$Age)

# Calculate bounds for outliers
age_lower_bound <- age_q1 - 1.5 * age_iqr
age_upper_bound <- age_q3 - 1.5 * age_iqr

7 Distribution of Income Before and After removing Outliers.

Visualization:

Boxplots + Density Plots Comparison.

# Create comparison dataset
combined_data <- bind_rows(
  mutate(data, Type = "Original Data"),
  mutate(filter(data, Income <= income_upper_bound), Type = "Without Outliers")
)

# Calculate summary statistics
stats <- combined_data %>%
  group_by(Type) %>%
  summarise(
    Mean = mean(Income),
    Median = median(Income),
    SD = sd(Income),
    .groups = 'drop'
  )


# Boxplot
boxplot <- ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = Type, y = Income, fill = Type)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = income_upper_bound, linetype = "dashed", color = "red", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_text(aes(x = 1.5, y = income_upper_bound + 5000,
              label = paste("Outlier Threshold = $", round(income_upper_bound, 2))),
            color = "red", size = 3.5) +
  geom_text(data = stats,
            aes(x = Type, y = max(combined_data$Income) * 0.9,
                label = paste("Mean = $", round(Mean, 0), "\nMedian = $", round(Median, 0))),
            vjust = 1, size = 3.5) +
  labs(title = "Income Distribution Comparison",
       subtitle = "Boxplot View with Outlier Threshold",
       x = "",
       y = "Income ($)") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#FF6B6B", "#4ECDC4")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10, color = "gray50"))

#  Density Plot
density <- ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = Income, fill = Type)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.6, color = NA) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = income_upper_bound, linetype = "dashed", color = "red", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_text(aes(x = income_upper_bound + 10000, y = 0.00005,
              label = paste("Outlier Threshold\n$", round(income_upper_bound, 2))),
            color = "red", size = 3.5) +
  annotate("text", x = Inf, y = Inf,
           label = paste("Original SD =", round(stats$SD[1], 2), "\nCleaned SD =", round(stats$SD[2], 2)),
           hjust = 1.1, vjust = 1.1, size = 3.5) +
  labs(title = "Income Density Comparison",
       subtitle = "Distribution Shape Before/After Outlier Removal",
       x = "Income ($)",
       y = "Density") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#FF6B6B", "#4ECDC4")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10, color = "gray50"))


# Side-by-side layout
grid.arrange(boxplot , density , ncol = 2)

# Create cleaned dataset
data_clean <- data %>% 
  filter(between(Income, income_lower_bound, income_upper_bound),
         between(Age, age_lower_bound, age_upper_bound))

8 Comprehensive Income Analysis.

Box plot + Density plot + Histogram.

# 1. First ensure both data frames have identical columns
common_cols <- intersect(names(data), names(data_clean))

# 2. Create modified versions with only common columns
data_sub <- data %>% 
  select(all_of(common_cols)) %>% 
  mutate(Type = "Original Data")

data_clean_sub <- data_clean %>% 
  select(all_of(common_cols)) %>% 
  mutate(Type = "Without Outliers")

# 3. Now safely combine
combined_data <- bind_rows(data_sub, data_clean_sub)
# Create comparison data
plot_data <- bind_rows(
  data %>% mutate(Group = "With Outliers"),
  data_clean %>% mutate(Group = "Without Outliers")
) %>%
  mutate(Group = factor(Group, levels = c("With Outliers", "Without Outliers")))

# Custom theme for consistency
custom_theme <- theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10, color = "gray40", hjust = 0.5),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 11),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )

# Enhanced boxplot
boxplot_enhanced <- ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Group, y = Income, fill = Group)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.8, width = 0.5, outlier.color = "red", outlier.shape = 8) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", shape = 18, size = 3, color = "black") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format()) +
  labs(
    title = "Income Distribution Comparison",
    subtitle = "Boxplots Showing Impact of Outlier Removal",
    x = "",
    y = "Income",
    caption = "Red stars show outliers | Black diamonds show means"
  ) +
  custom_theme +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# Enhanced density plot
density_enhanced <- ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Income, fill = Group)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.6, color = NA) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(income_lower_bound, income_upper_bound),
             linetype = "dashed", color = "red", alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9")) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = dollar_format()) +
  labs(
    title = "Income Density Comparison",
    subtitle = paste("Outlier bounds at", dollar(income_lower_bound), "and", dollar(income_upper_bound)),
    x = "Income",
    y = "Density",
    fill = "Dataset"
  ) +
  custom_theme

# Combined histogram with facets
histogram_enhanced <- ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Income, fill = Group)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(density)), bins = 30, alpha = 0.8,
                 position = "identity", color = "white") +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.2, color = "black") +
  facet_wrap(~Group, ncol = 1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9")) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = dollar_format()) +
  labs(
    title = "Income Distribution Histograms",
    subtitle = "With density curve overlay",
    x = "Income",
    y = "Density"
  ) +
  custom_theme

# Display plots
grid.arrange(boxplot_enhanced, density_enhanced, histogram_enhanced,
             ncol = 2,
             layout_matrix = rbind(c(1, 2), c(3, 3)),
             top = textGrob("Comprehensive Income Distribution Analysis",
                           gp = gpar(fontsize = 16, font = 2)))

combined_plot <- data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Income, Age)) %>%

10 Relationship Between Outliers in Income and Age

# Calculate bounds.
income_q1 <- quantile(data$Income, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
income_q3 <- quantile(data$Income, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
income_iqr <- income_q3 - income_q1
income_lower_bound <- income_q1 - 1.5 * income_iqr
income_upper_bound <- income_q3 + 1.5 * income_iqr

age_q1 <- quantile(data$Age, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
age_q3 <- quantile(data$Age, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
age_iqr <- age_q3 - age_q1
age_lower_bound <- age_q1 - 1.5 * age_iqr
age_upper_bound <- age_q3 + 1.5 * age_iqr

# Create outlier classification.
data <- data %>%
  mutate(
    outlier_type = case_when(
      Income < income_lower_bound & Age < age_lower_bound ~ "Low Both",
      Income < income_lower_bound & Age > age_upper_bound ~ "Low Income/High Age",
      Income > income_upper_bound & Age < age_lower_bound ~ "High Income/Low Age",
      Income > income_upper_bound & Age > age_upper_bound ~ "High Both",
      Income < income_lower_bound | Income > income_upper_bound ~ "Income Outlier",
      Age < age_lower_bound | Age > age_upper_bound ~ "Age Outlier",
      TRUE ~ "Normal" # This replaces what might have been NULL
    )
  )

# Enhanced scatterplot with controlled colors
ggplot(data, aes(x = Age, y = Income, color = outlier_type)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7, size = 2) +
  # Threshold lines (now properly colored)
  geom_hline(yintercept = c(income_lower_bound, income_upper_bound), 
             linetype = "dashed", color = "darkred", size = 0.7) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(age_lower_bound, age_upper_bound), 
             linetype = "dashed", color = "darkblue", size = 0.7) +
  # Custom color scale
  scale_color_manual(
    name = "Outlier Type",
    values = c(
      "Normal" = "gray70",
      "Income Outlier" = "#FF7F0E",  # Orange
      "Age Outlier" = "#1F77B4",     # Blue
      "Low Both" = "#2CA02C",        # Green
      "High Both" = "#D62728",       # Red
      "Low Income/High Age" = "#9467BD", # Purple
      "High Income/Low Age" = "#8C564B"  # Brown
    )
  ) +
  # Labels and titles
  labs(
    title = "Income vs Age with Outlier Identification",
    subtitle = "Dashed lines show outlier thresholds",
    x = "Age (years)",
    y = "Income (USD)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold")
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format())

11 Outliers by Age Group.

# Create age groups
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(age_group = cut(Age, breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 10), 
                         right = FALSE, 
                         labels = c("0-9", "10-19", "20-29", "30-39", 
                                   "40-49", "50-59", "60-69", "70-79", 
                                   "80-89", "90-99")))

# Count income outliers by age group
income_outliers_by_age <- data %>% 
  filter(Income < income_lower_bound | Income > income_upper_bound) %>% 
  count(age_group, name = "income_outliers")

# Count age outliers by age group (this is just for completeness)
age_outliers_by_age <- data %>% 
  filter(Age < age_lower_bound | Age > age_upper_bound) %>% 
  count(age_group, name = "age_outliers")

# Combine results
outlier_summary <- full_join(income_outliers_by_age, age_outliers_by_age, by = "age_group") %>% 
  replace_na(list(income_outliers = 0, age_outliers = 0))
